<br>
Often, when I was young, my Mom used to tell me, &quot;You can't see the forest cause of the trees.&quot;  Wise woman my Mom.  Wiser than I realized at a young age what she meant and the scope of that simple statement.  I still do that, and I'm not the only one.  My mind keeps thinking that trees make up the forest and that was my argument.<br>
<br>
What I am going to do is highlight the &quot;trees&quot; that have been debated and try to show you the &quot;forest&quot;.<br>
<br>
Tree: The war is all about oil.  Actually this is partially true but not in the way that anti-war paints the picture.  It's not about the greed of the U.S. to get their hands on Iraqi oil.  Oil just makes it much more complicated.<br>
<br>
Forest: Every country on the planet needs oil.  Oil is probably one of the most traded commodities on the global market.  Oil has a direct impact on the global economy.  A stable oil trade market keeps the global economy running smoothly.  Any large oil producing country threatening that economy in a sense threatens the global economy.  Saddam Hussein was a leader of a country sitting on top of one of the world's largest oil reserves.  Was he removed ONLY because of oil?  NO.  Did oil have something to do with it?  YES.<br>
<br>
Tree: The U.S. broke International Law attacking Iraq.  This is a real good one and a real tough one to debate.  But only tough to debate if you try and attack tree vs. tree.<br>
<br>
Forest: In order for the U.N. to actually be The Law, it has to enforce The Law.  The problem lies in the fact that those in the U.N. that make the law are often themselves breaking the law or wanting to turn the other cheek while someone else breaks the law.  We must remember that Iraq was under a cease-fire agreement.  We must remember that Iraq failed to honor the agreement for 12 years.  We must remember that Iraq kicked out the inspectors in 1998.  So if the Coalition &quot;broke&quot; the law, then Iraq &quot;broke&quot; it first.  If Iraq did NOT &quot;break&quot; the law, neither did the Coalition.<br>
<br>
Tree: No WMD in Iraq has been found yet.  The anti-war crowd keeps holding onto this argument to justify the war being wrong.<br>
<br>
Forest: Iraq had chemical and biological weapons that are unaccounted for.  If they still have them, then they have WMD.  If they don't, then they have no business running a country like Iraq when they can't even keep up with their own shit since they didn't provide any documentation to prove destroying it.  Argue it any way you want, they are either lying through their teeth OR totally incompetent.  Should lying to the U.N. Security Council warrant a regime change?  Should total incompetence warrant a regime change?  You betcha.<br>
<br>
Tree: Iraq harbors and supports terrorists.  The anti-war crowd has said repeatedly there was no proof that Saddam Hussein had links to terrorism.  The pro-war crowd says he did.<br>
<br>
Forest: If Iraq had no ties to terrorism, then what were all those guys doing up there in northern Iraq?  Then why did the Iraqi regime call upon terrorists to help fight off the infidels?  Denying it now is pure stupidity.<br>
<br>
Tree: Because of Coalition actions, why should any country like Russia or China ever obey U.N. resolutions?  Interesting argument.<br>
<br>
Forest: Because of the actions of the Coalition, a message was sent to the world that despite attempts to divide the U.N., they will be held accountable for their actions should enough people see their actions as a direct threat to peace in the world.  It is unfortunate that war sometimes is the only solution, but sometimes it IS the SOLUTION.<br>
<br>
This will probably be my last post about this war.  As far as I am concerned, the war in Iraq is over.  The regime is no longer in power and the Iraqi people are free.  Only time will tell the total outcome, but at least for now the future looks better than it did. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=140009" target="top">Ozzone - Noble Blade</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
